1. (A x B) ∪ {1, 3}
First, find A x B: {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}
Now, find the union with {1, 3}: {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4), 1, 3}

2. {1, 3} ∪ (A x B)
This is the same as the previous problem, so the result is the same: {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4), 1, 3}

3. (A ∪ {1}) x B
A ∪ {1} is just A since 1 is already in A: {1, 2}
Now, find the Cartesian product with B: {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

4. A x (B ∪ {3})
B ∪ {3} is just B since 3 is already in B: {3, 4}
Now, find the Cartesian product with A: {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

5. (A x B) ∪ (A x {3})
First, find A x {3}: {(1, 3), (2, 3)}
Now, find the union with A x B: {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}
